AUDIO: 'There\'s really only one thing I don\'t like about this project, and it\'s not that it\'s a fork, because I think you would have to make this a fork because the people at GDO don\'t obviously or don\'t uh on um always agree with people\'s UX changes. Although, I'

[05:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'honestly think that this is this is an an improvement across the board. Like I I don\'t think anybody would argue that this isn\'t a better layout, but I\'m curious if if you would would you like the old layout or do you like the idea'

[05:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'of being able to split tabs and split panes and so on? So each one gets their own inspector in their own tree. That is definitely a big part of it right here. Uh shaders, materials, resources, they all open as full workspaces, so they work just the same as first class'

[05:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'citizens like um when you\'re dealing with a 2D or a 3D scene. That is lovely as well. On top of that, the bottom drawer slides up over the workspace for the file system logs or any panels you want down there. So again, kind of a useful thing so that it\'s not attached'

[05:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'to an individual one. Uh so it it works well with this particular system. Uh and then also scenes and resources open faster. So you can see an example right here of opening up the TPS demo. GD Studio takes 3 seconds versus GDO 4.6'

[06:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'which takes about seven I think it was in this particular example. And in my experience is it actually does load resources about twice as fast. Now this is probably more low-level changes. I'

[06:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'don\'t know what has caused that speed up. Uh but one of those things that I this I would love to see contributed back to the core and you know that for sure. So in terms of what is GD Studio is new GDO engine project editor again'

[06:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'editor uh built with performance and UX improvements in mind. I started using GDAU in 2014 and loved it immediately. Node system feels intuitive and fun to work with. The editor itself always felt like it lacked direction and was constantly getting in my way. So he'

[06:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'decided to build his own version. Uh so what is difference? Biggest change. You\'re no longer limited to one view at a time. In the GDO editor, you switch between 2D, 3D, and script one at a time. And the inspector only ever shows for a single selection. In GD Studio,'

[06:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'each scene, script, or resource opens in its own tab, which you can arrange any way you like, even placed on a separate monitor. Uh oh, yeah. So you can dock away tabs as well. So you can come up here, right click and then detach out'

[07:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'that window and then move that off screen wherever you wish it to be or so on. So a lot of flexibility in their view system here. Uh okay. So uh why is it alpha? Most of the functionality'

[07:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'works but a few areas still need improving. The biggest one is add-ons. I\'m still refining the code to support as many editor add-ons as possible and some of them may not work yet because of the way uh they rely on specific UI node layouts. I will report add-on'

[07:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'compatibility status once that work is done. Uh so back up your project or use source control when working with this editor. Uh what version is this compatible? So right now projects made with 4.6.3 and there is also a 4.7 version as well.'

[07:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'It ships with the C# module by default by the way. Uh so you can also go back so you don\'t have to keep using GD editor. You can actually switch back to the GDO editor if you wish. Uh and then okay so why not merge? So it reworks'

[07:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'most of the editor systems using different programming principles than the way the editor is built today. mostly in style by Casey Murritorii and the handmade gang. This reworking will continue to go deeper and my main goal'

[08:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'is to simplify the code and improve performance. So this is the big one. Why not open source? I feel most comfortable working this way. I don\'t have the means monitoring and otherwise to maintain a public project. Keeping it closed lets me move fast and allow and follow the'

[08:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'direction I have in mind. So that is definitely the one big downside in this one. It is not an open source project. Uh so if he goes away, uh the project goes away. It\'s definitely one of those things you commit to, but at the same time, that doesn\'t really matter at the'

[08:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'end of the day because you can think of this as like a new tool on top. You\'re still using the same GDAU, same file formats and all that. It\'s just a different and improved editor on the front end. Honestly, I didn\'t expect'

